Selective Inference Example

Suppose that: \[\left[ \begin{array}{c} Y_\beta \\ Y_{\delta} \end{array} \right] \sim \mbox{N}\left( \left[ \begin{array}{c} \beta \\ \delta \end{array} \right], \left[ \begin{array}{cc} 1 & \rho \\ \rho & 1\\ \end{array} \right]\right), \quad A = \{|Y_\delta| > c\} \] The quantity \(U = Y_\delta - \rho Y_\beta\) is a sufficient statistic for \(\delta\) and we have \[\left.\left[ \begin{array}{c} Y_\beta \\ Y_{\delta} \end{array} \right] \right| (U=u) = \left[ \begin{array}{c} \beta + Z \\ u + \rho (\beta + Z) \end{array} \right], \quad Z \sim \mbox{N}(0,1)\]

In class we calculated the conditional distribution of \(Y_\beta\) under \(H_0\colon \beta = \beta_0\) given \(U=u\) and \(A\) or \(A^c\). The following R code implements the corresponding CDF:

conditionalCDF <- function(y, b, u, rho, crit, A) {
  L <- (-crit - u) / rho
  R <- (crit - u) / rho
  Phi_y <- pnorm(y - b)
  Phi_R <- pnorm(R - b)
  Phi_L <- pnorm(L - b)
  if(A) {
    denom <- 1 - Phi_R + Phi_L
    num1 <- (y < L) * Phi_y
    num2 <- ((y >= L) & (y <= R)) * Phi_L
    num3 <- (y > R) * (Phi_y - Phi_R + Phi_L)
  } else {
    denom <- Phi_R - Phi_L
    num1 <- (y < L) * 0
    num2 <- ((y >= L) & (y <= R)) * (Phi_y - Phi_L)
    num3 <- (y > R) * (Phi_R - Phi_L)
  }
  return((num1 + num2 + num3) / denom)
}

We can easily invert the proceeding to get a quantile function:

conditionalQuantile <- function(p, b, u, rho, crit, A) {
  L <- (-crit - u) / rho
  R <- (crit - u) / rho
  Phi_R <- pnorm(R - b)
  Phi_L <- pnorm(L - b)
  if(A) {
    denom <- 1 - Phi_R + Phi_L
    pstar <- Phi_L / denom
    argument <- p * denom + (p > pstar) * (Phi_R - Phi_L)
  } else {
    denom <- Phi_R - Phi_L
    argument <- p * denom + Phi_L
  }
  return(b + qnorm(argument))
}

Heres a function to plot the CDF:

plotCDF <- function(b, u, rho, crit, A) {
  eps <- 0.0001
  ylower <- conditionalQuantile(p = eps, b, u, rho, crit, A)
  yupper <- conditionalQuantile(p = 1 - eps, b, u, rho, crit, A)
  yseq <- seq(ylower, yupper, length.out = 501)
  Fseq <- conditionalCDF(yseq, b, u, rho, crit, A)
  plot(yseq, Fseq, type = 'l', xlab = 'y', ylab = 'CDF')
  abline(v = (-crit - u) / rho, lty = 2, col = 'red')
  abline(v = (crit - u) / rho, lty = 2, col = 'red')
}

and heres one to plot the quantile function:

plotQuantile <- function(b, u, rho, crit, A) {
  eps <- 0.0001
  pseq <- seq(eps, 1 - eps, length.out = 501)
  Qseq <- conditionalQuantile(pseq, b, u, rho, crit, A)
  plot(pseq, Qseq, type = 'l', xlab = 'p', ylab = 'Quantile')
  abline(h = (-crit - u) / rho, lty = 2, col = 'red')
  abline(h = (crit - u) / rho, lty = 2, col = 'red')
}

Now lets try a simple simulation experiment. First well set values of \(\beta\), \(\delta\), \(\rho\), \(c\) and the number of simulation draws:

b <- 0
d <- 1
r <- 0.4
crit <- qnorm(1 - 0.05 / 2)
n <- 1000000

Now we make \(n\) bivariate standard normal draws with correlation \(\rho\)

set.seed(1234)
y <- MASS::mvrnorm(n, c(b, d), Sigma = matrix(c(1, r, r, 1), 2, 2, byrow = TRUE))
Yb <- y[,1]
Yd <- y[,2]

The preceding are draws from the unconditional joint distribution of \(Y_\beta\) and and \(Y_\delta\). Now well condition on the event \(A\), by keeping only the subset of draws for which \(Y_\delta\) is larger in absolute value that \(c\).

yA <- y[abs(Yd) > crit,]
yA <- yA[sample(1:nrow(yA), 10000),]
Yb_A <- yA[,1]
Yd_A <- yA[,2]
U <- Yd_A - r * Yb_A

Notice the difference between the conditional and unconditional distributions of \(Y_\beta\):

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
hist(Yb)
abline(v = mean(Yb), col = 'red', lty = 2, lwd = 2)
hist(Yb_A)
abline(v = mean(Yb_A), col = 'red', lty = 2, lwd = 2)
par(mfrow = c(1, 1))

Suppose that we want to test against the one-sided alternative, namely \(H_0\colon \beta = 0\) versus \(H_1\colon \beta > 0\) with \(\alpha = 0.05\). Now well plot the critical value for a valid selective test. This is a function of the observed value of \(U\). Lets see how it compares to the critical value wed get if we hadnt conditioned on \(A\):

Useq <- seq(-4, 4, 0.01)
critical_values <- conditionalQuantile(0.95, b, Useq, rho = r, crit, A = TRUE)
plot(Useq, critical_values, type = 'l', xlab = 'U', ylab = 'Critical Value')
abline(h = qnorm(0.95), col = 'red', lty = 2, lwd = 2)

Now lets check that this works in our simulation study. First well construct the observed sufficient statistics, and then well calculate the selective critical value for each one:

U <- Yd_A - r * Yb_A
critical_values <- conditionalQuantile(0.95, b, U, rho = r, crit, A = TRUE)

Now well carry out the test: rejecting if \(Y_\beta\) exceeds the conditional conditional critical value, given \(U=u\). Since the null is true, we should reject with probability \(\alpha = 0.05\)

mean(Yb_A > critical_values)
[1] 0.0508

Now compare this to what we would have gotten if we had ignored the effects of our first-step selection procedure on subsequent inference:

mean(Yb_A > qnorm(0.95))
[1] 0.1295
